<setup>
  <selectFromSequence name="k" from="0.1" to="0.5" step="0.1"/>
  <selectFromSequence name="m" from="3" to="5" step="1" exclude="$z"/>
  <function name="f" variable="t">$k*t*e^(-$k*t)</function>
  <function name="u" variable="t">$k*t</function>
  <function name="du" variable="t">$k</function>
  <function name="dv" variable="t">e^(-$k*t)</function>
  <function name="v" variable="t">-1/$k*e^(-$k*t)</function>
  <function name="F" variable="t">-t*e^(-$k*t)-1/$k*e^(-$k*t)</function>
  <math name="mu">1/$k</math>
  <math name="meanwait">1 - e^(-1)</math>
</setup>

<p>
  At a customer support call center, the fraction of people who wait between time <m>t = a</m> and <m>t = b</m> (in minutes) to have their call answered is given by the definite integral 
  <me>
    \int_a^b $k \, e^{-$k t} \, dt.
  </me>
  Note that the function <m>p(t) = $k e^{-$k t}</m> has the property that <m>\int_0^\infty $k \, e^{-$k t}  \, dt = 1</m>.
</p>  

<p>
  It turns out that the average (or <term>mean</term>) wait time, <m>\mu</m> is given by the improper integral
  <me>
    \mu = \int_0^\infty $k t \cdot e^{-$k t}  \, dt.
  </me>
  Through the steps below, we find the exact value of <m>\mu</m>.
</p>  

<p>
  <ol marker="a.">
    <li>
      <p>
        First, we find an antiderivative for <m>f(t) = $k t \cdot e^{-$k t}</m> using integration by parts.  Letting <m>u = $k t</m> and <m>dv =  e^{-$k t} \, dt</m>, it follows (applying the integration by parts formula) that 
      </p>
      <p>
        <m>\int $k t \cdot e^{-$k t} \, dt =</m><mathInput name="uv"/><m> - \int</m><mathInput name="vdu"/><m>dt</m> <answer><award><when>$uv = $u*$v and $vdu = $v*$du</when></award></answer>,
      </p>
      <p>
        and then evaluating the final integral and stating the full antiderivative without integral signs,
      </p>
      <p>
        <m>\int $k t \cdot e^{-$k t} \, dt =</m><mathInput name="int"/><answer><award><when>$int=$F</when></award></answer>
      </p>      
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Next, use the antiderivative from (a), the First FTC, and appropriate limit notation to find the exact value of 
        <me>
          \mu = \int_0^\infty $k t \cdot e^{-$k t}  \, dt.
        </me>
      </p>
      <p>
        <m>\mu = </m><mathInput name="mean"/><answer><award><when>$mean=$mu</when></award></answer>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Find the fraction, <m>K</m>, of customers who wait <m>\mu</m> minutes or fewer.
      </p>
      <p>
        <m>K = </m><mathInput name="half"/><answer allowedErrorInNumbers="0.01" allowedErrorIsAbsolute><award><when>$half=$meanwait</when></award></answer>
      </p>      
    </li>
  </ol>
</p>